result.execSummary:
The defendant Gregory J. Jung was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Forgery-Uttering [Modifiers: Repeater, PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.38(2).
  • Forgery-Uttering [Modifiers: Repeater, PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.38(2).
  • Forgery-Uttering [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime, Repeater], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.38(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Notice to Withdraw-Representation-Complete filed by Atty William Weiland
Count 3

(Count 3) Attorney William George Weiland in court. Defendant Gregory J. Jung appeared by phone. Prosecuting Atty Michael Daniel Zell appeared for State of Wisconsin.
Both files heard: 16CF7 (sentencing on Count 3 only) and 15CF375 ( to address sentence credit)
9:03 a.m.  Court calls the cases. 

Court reviews the files. 
It is the courts understanding that the defendant did not need to be present today. 
Atty Zell makes statements to the Court.  All parties agreed to have the defendant appear by telephone. 
Atty Weiland concurs. 
Court questions the defendant. 
Defendant concurs. 

Court questions if victim has received notice. 
Atty Zell make statements re: victim not having responded or requested notice. 
State has complied with Victim Notification Statutes.
Victim is not present.

Atty Zell makes sentencing arguments to the Court. 
Atty Weiland does not wish to be heard. 
Defendant makes statements to the Court.  Wishes to address sentence credit. 
Court reviews the file further. 
Atty Zell makes statements.  Agrees what credit should be.  Written stipulation has not been signed yet.  Agrees there are 621 days credit on 15CF375.  
Court notes credit should be determined by DOC on imposed and stayed sentences.  Questions Atty Weiland. 
Atty Weiland responds.  Believed they needed to reach an agreement on 15CF375 for credit. 
Court believed they would be addressing sentencing credit in 16CF7. 
Atty Weiland makes statements and agrees there are 408 days credit as of the time of the SAR hearing on November 28, 2018. 
Defendant agrees with that amount. 
Court questions the defendant re: credit given by the DOC on 15CF375.  
Defendant indicates DOC only gave him 90 days credit on 15CF375.  He is disputing that amount. 
Court questions Atty Weiland. 
Atty Weiland indicates on 15CF375 they had calculated 621 days of credit.  
Court reviews the SAR packet in 15CF375. 
Atty Weiland makes statements.  Incarcerated 9/25/15 to 9/27/16 which is 368 days.  Also incarcerated on 3/20/17 to 11/28/17 which is 253 days. 
Court reviews the file in 15CF375.  
Court questions Atty Weiland further. 
Atty Weiland responds.  
Court questions the defendant re: Stipulation and Order in 15CF375.
Defendant indicates he sat on the bond for that case. 
Atty Zell makes statements.  At that time, the defendant was also serving a sentence.  Once he starts serving his sentence, the credit for the bond does not count. 
Atty Weiland makes additional statements to the Court.  It appears that he would not get the credit because he started serving his sentence pursuant to the Beets case. 
Court questions the defendant and informs the defendant of credit not received at the time a sentence starts, the cases sever. 
Defendant makes statements to the Court. 
Atty Weiland speaks with his client re: credit. 
Defendant makes additional statements to the Court re: the credit for the later dates. 
Court informs the defendant he does not have enough information to address the jail credit on 15CF375.  
Atty Weiland makes additional statements to the Court.  Parties were not aware of the previous 101 days of credit that was stipulated too or that he was potentionally serving a sentencing at that time.  So there may need to be some recalculations of the sentence credit. 
Atty Zell makes additional statements.  Does not believe they have enough information at this time to stipulate to the credit in 15CF375 today. 
Defendant questions what credit he will be given on 16CF7 count 3. 
Atty Weiland makes statements.  

BY THE COURT:  
16CF7 Count 3 - 
4 years prison with 2 years Initial Confinement followed by 2 years Extended Supervision, concurrent with all other sentences. 
408 days credit as of 11/28/2017.  
Pay costs including the DNA surcharge. 
Conditions of Extended Supervision will be identical to the terms of Extended Supervision that he has in his other cases. 
Eligible for CIP and SAP programs. 
Copy of Written Explanation is to be sent to the Defendant. 

JOC to be amended to reflect he was sentenced on Counts 1, 2 & 3.  JOC for all 3 counts should reflect 408 days pre-trial incarceration credit as of 11/28/2017. 

With regards to 15CF375 - The court was not aware that there was any dispute prior to todays date since there had been a stipulation re: credit.  
Court notes the DOC in the Revo Order and WArrant refers to this case and talks about credit with holds from 3/20/2017 to the court date.  It did not distinguish out the files and credits or the stipulation for the 101 days.  Atty Weiland may want to speak to his client with what DOC has given him and work on a stipulation.  If there is a dispute on that matter, then a motion will need to be filed with supporting documentation and a hearing will be conducted. 

Atty Weiland questions the defendant re: revoked case back in 1/4/2016.  
Defendant indicates it was 10CF184.
Court asks counsel to review that information.
